This is just the legal issue anyways - The technical side of things renders the legal side moot anyways, since technically, its possible to disguise running tasks such that they are virtually impossible to identify. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhasinfirestorm@themagicianstower>Rhasin Firestorm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 1180<br> <font color=#333333>(11/1/02 6:33:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7687.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: This isn't good...</span><hr size=1> Verant doesn't have to do any such thing as scan your computer's harddrive for the program. There are a few simple security changes that could be done that would permit VI to maintain a tighter control over the data being sent without breaking the way things work.<br>
<br>
1) Tracking Information and Mob Location. This information is important for knowing if you can see a creature, either visually or on Track. Simple changes:<br>
<br>
1a) Visual range - Only broadcast data for mobs within X feet of you. Server load goes up some, but spreading out the work for zones over a few more servers could alieviate that work.<br>
<br>
1b) Tracking range - When a tracker hits 'Track', the request is sent, and the servers calculate 'in bulk' the mobs that the tracker can see based on range. This decreases the need to broadcast all mob data at once (ie: less bandwidth required) and functions just as well with the way Track works (it doesn't read live updates, only when you hit 'Track').<br>
<br>
This seems to be simple enough a fix. I'm sure there are some issues with doing this, but depending on how horrific they are, they can be corrected. This also destroys one of the main purpose of ShowEQ. To listen to all zone data and report mob locations.<br>
<br>
How about scanning for ShowEQ? There's another fix that could be put into place to stop that.<br>
<br>
2) Check the Network Layer of the computer you're on. If there are any sockets running in 'raw' or promiscious mode (detectable, typically), simply refuse to start. If there are not, continue normal startup. Generally, especially with encrypted communications, missing the first segment of negotiation and any keys that may be transmitted can screw with the sniffer's ability to listen to the packets. This method means you are not transmitting any information, and the data integrity is (more) secured, as the client will not launch if it thinks it's being watched. Also, no hard drive scanning takes place, only a brief scan of the network layer.<br>
<br>
It's pretty sad that people feel they need to resort to cheating to play a game. It's even worse that the people who help that cheating resort to declaring war on the company when the company decides that they no longer wish to permit it as easy as before. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://&quot;http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=52886&quot;"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ninjacorp.com/Rhasin_sig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=artulyn1>Artulyn1</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 143<br> <font color=#333333>(11/1/02 6:43:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7687.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: This isn't good...</span><hr size=1> The problem with EQW is that there are people that will use it to run &quot;trainer&quot; programs in the background to hack EQ and that's why $OE is so against EQW. It completely gets around their keyboard hijack that prevents you from minimizing EQ or switching between EQ and another program. Of all the programs I use regularly, EQ is the only one that takes over my computer and doesn't let me multitask. Frankly that's about the only thing I really dislike about EQ. <p><br>
